<body>
    <h1>Definitions of Ready and Done</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h2 id=3D"DefinitionsofReadyandDone-Epics-Ready"><strong>Epics - Re=
ady</strong></h2>
<ul class=3D"inline-task-list" data-inline-tasks-content-id=3D"72155141">
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"21"><strong>Epics overview</strong>: A clear and=
 concise description of the Epic, outlining its purpose, goals, and expecte=
d outcomes.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"1552"><strong>Initial Architecture design: </str=
ong>A preliminary technical architectural design to deliver the solution</l=
i>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"22"><strong>Dependencies identified</strong>: An=
y dependencies or prerequisites required for the successful implementation =
of the Epic should be identified and addressed.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"23"><strong>Scope and boundaries</strong>: The b=
oundaries of the Epic should be well-defined and agreed upon, ensuring a cl=
ear understanding of what is included and what is not.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"24"><strong>Decomposition plan</strong>: The Epi=
c may need to be decomposed into smaller, manageable user stories to enable=
 incremental delivery. The plan for decomposing the Epic should be discusse=
d and agreed upon.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"25"><strong>Prioritization</strong>: The Epic sh=
ould be prioritized within the product backlog, aligning it with the overal=
l project goals.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"26"><strong>Stakeholder alignment:</strong> Rele=
vant stakeholders should review and provide input on the Epic to ensure ali=
gnment with their expectations and needs.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"27"><strong>Rough estimation</strong>: A prelimi=
nary estimation of effort and complexity should be performed to give the te=
am and stakeholders an idea of the scale of the Epic.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"28"><strong>High-level acceptance criteria</stro=
ng>: Broad acceptance criteria should be established to guide the developme=
nt of individual user stories within the Epic.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"29"><strong>Definition of Done</strong>: The tea=
m should establish a shared understanding of what it means for the Epic to =
be considered "done" to ensure a consistent level of completeness.<br><br>
It is important to note that the Definition of Ready for an Epic can vary d=
epending on the team and project context. Teams should adapt and refine the=
ir Definition of Ready as they gain experience and learn from previous iter=
ations.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"DefinitionsofReadyandDone-Epics-Done"><strong>Epics - Done</stron=
g></h2>
<ul class=3D"inline-task-list" data-inline-tasks-content-id=3D"72155141">
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"30">All user stories within the Epic have been c=
ompleted and meet their respective DoDs.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"31">The Epic has been reviewed and accepted by s=
takeholders, ensuring alignment with their expectations.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"32">All acceptance criteria for the user stories=
 within the Epic have been met.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"33">The Epic has been tested thoroughly, includi=
ng both functional and non-functional testing.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"34">The code associated with the Epic has been r=
eviewed and meets the team's coding standards and best practices.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"35">Any necessary documentation or user guides r=
elated to the Epic have been created or updated.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"36">The Epic has been integrated and tested with=
in the larger system or application, ensuring compatibility and functionali=
ty.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"37">Performance testing, if applicable, has been=
 conducted and the Epic meets the required performance criteria.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"38">Any outstanding known defects or issues rela=
ted to the Epic have been addressed or documented appropriately.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"39">The Epic has been signed off by the Product =
Owner or relevant stakeholders as complete and ready for release or deliver=
y.</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p>It's important to note that the DoD for an Epic may differ from the DoD =
for individual user stories, as it encompasses a larger scope. The specific=
 items in the Definition of Done may vary depending on the team, project, a=
nd organizational context.</p>
<h2 id=3D"DefinitionsofReadyandDone-Features-Ready"><strong>Features - Read=
y</strong></h2>
<ul class=3D"inline-task-list" data-inline-tasks-content-id=3D"72155141">
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"40"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default"><s=
trong>Description</strong>: The Feature has a clear and concise description=
 that communicates its purpose and expected outcome.</span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"41"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default"><s=
trong>Acceptance Criteria</strong>: The acceptance criteria for the Feature=
 are defined and agreed upon by the development team and stakeholders, ensu=
ring a shared understanding of what needs to be accomplished.</span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"42"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default"><s=
trong>Dependencies</strong>: Any dependencies or prerequisites required for=
 implementing the Feature are identified and resolved or planned for approp=
riately.</span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"43"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default"><s=
trong>Estimates and Prioritization</strong>: The effort required to impleme=
nt the Feature has been estimated, and its priority has been determined wit=
hin the product backlog.</span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"44"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default"><s=
trong>Design and UI</strong>: The necessary design details and user interfa=
ce specifications, such as mockups or wireframes, are provided to guide the=
 development process.</span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"45"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default"><s=
trong>Stakeholder Alignment</strong>: The Feature has been reviewed and app=
roved by the relevant stakeholders, ensuring alignment with their expectati=
ons and needs.</span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"46"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default"><s=
trong>Testability</strong>: The Feature is testable, and any specific testi=
ng requirements or considerations are identified.</span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"47"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default"><s=
trong>Definition of Done</strong>: The team has a shared understanding of w=
hat it means for the Feature to be considered "done" and meets the team's D=
efinition of Done criteria.</span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"48"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default"><s=
trong>Backlog Refinement</strong>: The Feature has been discussed and refin=
ed, ensuring that it is sufficiently understood by the team.</span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"71"><strong style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" cla=
ss=3D"legacy-color-text-default">Dependencies and Risks</strong><span style=
=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-default">: Any poten=
tial risks or dependencies associated with the Feature have been identified=
 and addressed to mitigate their impact.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><br>
It is important to note that the specific criteria within the Definition of=
 Ready for Features can vary based on the team's preferences, project requi=
rements, and Agile methodology being followed.</p>
<h2 id=3D"DefinitionsofReadyandDone-Features-Done"><strong>Features - Done<=
/strong></h2>
<ul class=3D"inline-task-list" data-inline-tasks-content-id=3D"72155141">
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"50"><strong>Code implementation</strong>: The fe=
ature's code has been developed and meets the team's coding standards and b=
est practices.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"51"><strong>Unit testing</strong>: The feature h=
as been thoroughly unit tested to ensure that it functions correctly and as=
 expected.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"52"><strong>Integration testing:</strong> The fe=
ature has been integrated into the larger system or application and passes =
integration tests to verify compatibility and functionality.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"53"><strong>Acceptance criteria met:</strong> Th=
e feature has met all the agreed-upon acceptance criteria, as defined in th=
e user story or feature requirements.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"54"><strong>System testing:</strong> The feature=
 has undergone system or end-to-end testing to ensure that it works harmoni=
ously with other components or systems within the application.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"55"><strong>User interface (UI) review:</strong>=
 If applicable, the UI of the feature has been reviewed and approved by the=
 stakeholders for usability, consistency, and adherence to design guideline=
s.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"56"><strong>Performance testing:</strong> The fe=
ature has been tested to meet the required performance standards, such as r=
esponse time, scalability, or resource usage.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"57"><strong>Documentation:</strong> The necessar=
y documentation, such as user guides, API documentation, or technical speci=
fications, has been created or updated to reflect the changes introduced by=
 the feature.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"58"><strong>Quality assurance review:</strong> T=
he feature has passed quality assurance review processes, including code re=
views and peer reviews, to ensure its quality and maintainability.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"59"><strong>Stakeholder approval:</strong> The f=
eature has been reviewed and approved by the stakeholders, indicating their=
 satisfaction with the delivered functionality.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"60"><strong>Regression testing:</strong> The fea=
ture has not introduced any new defects or regression issues in existing fu=
nctionality, verified through regression testing.</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"61"><strong>Deployment readiness:</strong> The f=
eature is ready for deployment and release, including relevant configuratio=
n changes and deployment instructions.</li>
</ul>
<p>It is important to adapt the Definition of Done to fit the specific need=
s and context of the development team and project. As such, the actual item=
s and criteria in the Definition of Done may vary.</p>
<h2 id=3D"DefinitionsofReadyandDone-UPDATED-Userstories-Ready"><strong>UPDA=
TED - User stories - Ready</strong></h2>
<ul class=3D"inline-task-list" data-inline-tasks-content-id=3D"72155141">
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"62"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-green2"><em=
><strong>User story title and description:</strong> The user story should h=
ave a clear and concise title that represents the feature or functionality =
being developed. The description should provide enough context and detail f=
or the development team to understand the user's needs.</em></span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"63"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-green2"><em=
><strong>Acceptance criteria:</strong> The specific conditions or requireme=
nts that need to be met for the user story to be considered complete should=
 be defined. These criteria serve as measurable outcomes or tests to verify=
 that the user story has been implemented correctly.</em></span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"64"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-green2"><em=
><strong>User value:</strong> The user story should demonstrate value or so=
lve a problem for the end user. It should align with the overall goals and =
objectives of the product or project.</em></span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"65"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-green2"><em=
><strong>Dependencies identified:</strong> Any dependencies on other user s=
tories, features, or external factors should be identified, and plans to ad=
dress these dependencies should be in place. This ensures that there are no=
 roadblocks to completing the user story.</em></span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"66"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-green2"><em=
><strong>Estimation:</strong> The development team should have estimated th=
e effort and complexity required to implement the user story. This enables =
proper planning and prioritization during sprint or iteration planning.</em=
></span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"67"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-green2"><em=
><strong>Size and scope:</strong> The user story should be appropriately si=
zed to fit within a single sprint or iteration. It should have a clear scop=
e that is manageable and achievable within the time frame.</em></span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"68"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-green2"><em=
><strong>Testability:</strong> The user story should be testable, meaning t=
hat it can be adequately validated against the defined acceptance criteria.=
 Any specific testing requirements or considerations should be identified.<=
/em></span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"69"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-green2"><em=
><strong>Stakeholder input and involvement:</strong> The user story should =
have been reviewed and approved by the relevant stakeholders, ensuring thei=
r agreement on the expected outcomes.</em></span></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"70"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-green2"><em=
><strong>Definition of Done alignment:</strong> The user story should align=
 with the team's Definition of Done, ensuring a common understanding of the=
 level of completeness required for the user story.</em></span></li>
</ul>
<p><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-green2"><em>It's important to note that=
 the Definition of Ready can vary across teams and projects. The specific e=
lements may be tailored to fit the team's needs and development process.</e=
m></span></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default"><strong>The criteria that a sp=
ecific user story has to meet before being considered for estimation or inc=
lusion into a sprint.</strong></span></p>
<p><strong>When story is considered to be "ready" for development</strong><=
/p>
<ul class=3D"inline-task-list" data-inline-tasks-content-id=3D"72155141">
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"8">User story is <strong>Independent</strong>
<ul>
<li>Dependencies are identified</li>
<li>All known blockers are removed</li>
</ul></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"9">User story is <strong>Negotiable</strong></li=
>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"10">User story is <strong>Valuable</strong>
<ul>
<li>User story is clearly understood by the whole squad and understand WHY =
we are doing it.</li>
</ul></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"11">User story is <strong>Estimable</strong>
<ul>
<li>User story is broken down appropriately and small enough to be able to =
estimate.</li>
<li>User story should have enough details for the squad to estimate.</li>
<li>Acceptance criteria are clearly outlined.</li>
</ul></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"12">User story is <strong>Sized-Appropriately</s=
trong>
<ul>
<li>User story is sized, estimated and feasible to complete within a sprint=
</li>
<li>User story's size is defined by Dev Team</li>
</ul></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"13">User story is <strong>Testable</strong>
<ul>
<li>User story has a test strategy and know what level of test coverage we =
are expecting:
<ul>
<li>Manual</li>
<li>Unit</li>
<li>Feature, E2E (Liveflo)</li>
<li>Integration (I.e. interaction between our applications including with t=
hird parties + integration points with higher environment)</li>
<li>Regression</li>
<li>Smoke (I.e. does the website load after a deployment)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"14">User story is <strong>Measurable</strong>
<ul>
<li>Success metrics are identified</li>
</ul></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"18">User story is <strong>Releasable</strong>
<ul>
<li>Release plan defined and understood by the whole squad (e.g. WIP)</li>
</ul></li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"19">User story does not have an impact on Securi=
ty and Performance</li>
<li data-inline-task-id=3D"20">Internal and External communications are pla=
nned
<ul>
<li>Awareness and approval of the changes (if applicable)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"DefinitionsofReadyandDone-Userstories-Done"><strong>User stories =
- </strong><strong>Done</strong></h2>
<p><strong><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default">The agreed upon accept=
ance criteria that the Product Owner will use to accept the product increme=
nt at the end of the sprint.</span></strong></p>
<p><strong>Pull Request Stage:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">All switchable configuration parameters are present in Hieradata for the =
project, and documented in the Readme file.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">secrets.example.json or equivalent is fully up to date.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">Readme file is updated.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">No secrets are present.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">You have tested your own code on the Dev environment.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">Any code refactoring that affects other squads has been communicated to t=
he applicable squad/s. (Add a member of that squad to your pull request if =
required.)</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">In-house algorithms or custom functionality are sufficiently unit tested.=
</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">Solving MEND, Dependabot or any reported security issues on your feature =
branch.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">If any API's are updated or added, make sure the swagger docs are updated=
 for those API endpoints</span></li>
</ul>
<p><br><strong>Post Testing Stage:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">Acceptance Criteria - AC checked and met.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">Stakeholders - Must have gone through PO/stakeholder feedback.</span></li=
>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">Code has been through the testing process.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">End-to-end test coverage acceptable.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">Further tasks - Follow up work added to board.(Including Technical debt -=
 any accepted technical debts or defects have a relevant backlog item to wo=
rk on).</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">GDPR compliant - We are fully compliant and have no sensitive data in log=
s for example.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">Pipeline is green - Unit testing/ integration tests passed.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"legacy-color-text-blue3=
">Solving MEND, Dependabot or any reported security issues in Main branch.<=
/span></li>
